4413 14.3161 17.2044 14 18 14Z" fill="currentColor"></path><path d="M13 14.5H11V20.5H13V14.5Z" fill="currentColor"></path><path d="M12 13C12.5523 13 13 12.5523 13 12C13 11.4477 12.5523 11 12 11C11.4477 11 11 11.4477 11 12C11 12.5523 11.4477 13 12 13Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></button><button aria-label="email" class="react-share__ShareButton" style="background-color:transparent;border:none;padding:0;font:inherit;color:inherit;cursor:pointer"><div class="group"><span class="sr-only fixed">Axios on email</span><svg class="group-hover:text-white text-soft-black-core" height="32" width="32" viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none"><circle class="stroke-current text-accent-blue-tint" cx="16" cy="16" r="15.5"></circle><circle class="group-hover:fill-soft-black-core" cx="16" cy="16" r="15.5" fill="none"></circle><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M20 12H12C11.6253 12 11.297 12.2089 11.1258 12.5159C11.1819 12.5305 11.2364 12.5552 11.2867 12.5904L16 15.8897L20.7133 12.5904C20.7636 12.5552 20.8181 12.5305 20.8742 12.5159C20.703 12.2089 20.3747 12 20 12ZM21 13.6103L16.2867 16.9096C16.1146 17.0301 15.8854 17.0301 15.7133 16.9096L11 13.6103V19C11 19.55 11.45 20 12 20H20C20.55 20 21 19.55 21 19V13.6103Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></button></div></div><figure class="m-0" data-cy="au-image"><a aria-label="https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif" class="font-regular font-sans leading-none inline-flex items-center no-underline Anchor_anchor__Gw9JU Anchor_image__6LPnZ" href=""><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;overflow:hidden;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;position:relative"><span style="box-sizing:border-box;display:block;width:initial;height:initial;background:none;opacity:1;border:0;margin:0;padding:0;padding-top:56.25%"></span><img data-cy="StoryImage" alt="Illustration of a tombstone with a text message bubble." src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" decoding="async" data-nimg="responsive" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%"/><noscript><img data-cy="StoryImage" alt="Illustration of a tombstone with a text message bubble." sizes="100vw" srcSet="https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=320 320w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=320 320w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=640 640w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=640 640w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=768 768w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=768 768w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1024 1024w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1024 1024w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1366 1366w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1366 1366w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1600 1600w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1600 1600w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1920 1920w, https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1920 1920w" src="https://images.axios.com/gNUvtuulio47SLiGT4yins6Ozkw=/0x0:1920x1080/1920x1080/2022/07/12/1657650542387.gif?w=1920" decoding="async" data-nimg="responsive" style="position:absolute;top:0;left:0;bottom:0;right:0;box-sizing:border-box;padding:0;border:none;margin:auto;display:block;width:0;height:0;min-width:100%;max-width:100%;min-height:100%;max-height:100%" loading="lazy"/></noscript></span></a><figcaption class="pt-3 text-caption font-sans text-soft-black-shade">Illustration: Shoshana Gordon/Axios</figcaption></figure><div class="DraftjsBlocks_draftjs__jDHy3"><p>Creepy or cool? New products that let people keep relatives &quot;alive&quot; via AI are proliferating — offering, say, an interactive conversation with a recently departed dad who took the time to record a video interview before he passed.</p><p><strong>Why it matters: </strong>As interest in genealogy and <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="ancestry" data-vars-click-url="https://www.axios.com/2020/12/01/slavery-ancestor-project-to-expand" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.axios.com/2020/12/01/slavery-ancestor-project-to-expand" target="_self">ancestry</a> <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="proliferates" data-vars-click-url="https://www.ft.com/content/750c4ba2-71ae-4b9f-9bfb-ca580acb7c0c" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.ft.com/content/750c4ba2-71ae-4b9f-9bfb-ca580acb7c0c" target="_blank">proliferates</a>, these tools let families preserve memories and personal connections through generations — even giving children a sense of the physical presence of a relative who died before they were born.</p><ul><li>The tools are also being used to record the memories of noteworthy people: celebrities, Holocaust survivors, etc. </li></ul><p><strong>One such tool, <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="StoryFile" data-vars-click-url="https://storyfile.com/" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://storyfile.com/" target="_blank">StoryFile</a>, was notably used</strong> at the late actor Ed Asner&#x27;s <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="memorial service" data-vars-click-url="https://www.sagaftra.org/remembering-ed-asner#:~:text=Friends%2C%20colleagues%20and%20family%20members,and%20Frances%20Fisher%2C%20and%20others." data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.sagaftra.org/remembering-ed-asner#:~:text=Friends%2C%20colleagues%20and%20family%20members,and%20Frances%20Fisher%2C%20and%20others." target="_blank">memorial service</a>, where mourners were invited to &quot;converse&quot; with the deceased at an interactive display that featured video and audio he recorded over several days before he died.</p><ul><li>&quot;Nothing could prepare me for what I was going to witness when I saw it,&quot; Matt Asner, the actor&#x27;s son, told Axios.</li><li>The &quot;Lou Grant&quot; actor had used StoryFile to record an oral history; the product then employs AI to enable &quot;conversations&quot; based on subjects&#x27; answers to myriad questions.</li></ul><p><strong>At Asner&#x27;s memorial,</strong> &quot;many people just stopped by and asked a question or a couple questions,&quot; including Jason Alexander of &quot;Seinfeld&quot; fame, said Matt Asner, a TV and movie producer who now runs the Ed Asner Family Center, a nonprofit for people with special needs.</p><ul><li>&quot;Actually, you can&#x27;t just ask one question,&quot; he observed. &quot;That&#x27;s the great thing about it, is it draws you in — because the personality is there.&quot;</li><li>Ed Asner, a former head of the Screen Actors Guild, had &quot;covered everything — his childhood, work history, political history, family life,&quot; his son said. </li><li>While a few mourners were &quot;a little creeped out by it,&quot; the conversational video was &quot;like having him in the room,&quot; Matt Asner said. &quot;The great majority of people were just blown away by it.&quot;</li></ul><figure><img alt="An image of the actor Ed Asner at his memorial service." height="2552" id="0d0b6dd3-e76e-4381-8b51-06e2d30963f5" src="https://images.axios.com/1AHKssJgdK_KC2zPooGOSzPezF8=/2022/07/13/1657680281922.jpg" width="2362"/><figcaption>The actor Ed Asner appears on screen at his memorial service. Photo courtesy of StoryFile</figcaption></figure><p><strong>The big picture: </strong>StoryFile is perhaps the most robust of a growing number of tools that help people create interactive digital memories of relatives. Many of them don&#x27;t require the relative to be alive during setup.</p><ul><li>Amazon recently showed off an experimental Alexa <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="feature" data-vars-click-url="https://www.npr.org/2022/06/23/1107079194/amazon-alexa-dead-relatives-voice" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.npr.org/2022/06/23/1107079194/amazon-alexa-dead-relatives-voice" target="_blank">feature</a> that can read books aloud in the voice of a late relative, extrapolating from a snippet of that person&#x27;s recorded voice. </li><li>MyHeritage, the ancestry-tracing site, now offers &quot;<a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="Deep Nostalgia" data-vars-click-url="https://www.myheritage.com/deep-nostalgia" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.myheritage.com/deep-nostalgia" target="_blank">Deep Nostalgia</a>,&quot; a tool for animating old-timey photographs of your relatives.</li><li><a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="HereAfter AI" data-vars-click-url="https://www.hereafter.ai/" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.hereafter.ai/" target="_blank">HereAfter AI</a> lets you record stories about yourself and pair them with photographs — so family members can ask you about your life and experiences.</li><li>Microsoft has obtained a patent to create &quot;chatbots&quot; that mimic individual people (dead or alive) based on their social media posts and text messages, <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="per" data-vars-click-url="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2021/02/04/chat-bots-reincarnation-dead/" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2021/02/04/chat-bots-reincarnation-dead/" target="_blank">per</a> the Washington Post. </li></ul><p><strong>How it works: </strong>With StoryFile, a user sits for a video interview and answers a series of questions. </p><ul><li>The company produces an archive that can be watched sequentially or used in a Q&amp;A format.</li><li>When a question is asked, the AI technology retrieves relevant video content to create an answer, picking out clips from the available footage.</li></ul><p><strong>The company was co-founded</strong> by oral historian Stephen Smith, who used to run Steven Spielberg&#x27;s Shoah Foundation and specializes in preserving the memories of Holocaust survivors.</p><ul><li>&quot;In its most optimal state, the idea of StoryFile is you should be able to speak to anyone, anytime, anywhere that you wouldn’t normally have access to,&quot; Smith tells Axios.</li></ul><span id="midStoryAd" data-ad-status="AD"></span><ul><li>&quot;Maybe you don’t have access to grandma because she’s passed away, but you can still learn her story, feel a sense of connection to her.&quot;</li><li>StoryFile is also building an<a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text=" archive of public figures" data-vars-click-url="https://storyfile.com/gallery/" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://storyfile.com/gallery/" target="_blank"> archive of public figures</a> who have sat for interviews. (<a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="Try asking a question " data-vars-click-url="https://life.storyfile.com/" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://life.storyfile.com/" target="_blank">Try asking a question </a>of very-much-alive William Shatner.)</li></ul><p><strong>Between the lines: </strong>These types of programs are already growing familiar through deepfakes, science fiction, and <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="rock concerts that use holograms" data-vars-click-url="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/magazine/hologram-musicians.html" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/07/magazine/hologram-musicians.html" target="_blank">rock concerts that use holograms</a> to bring back dead performers like Buddy Holly.</p><ul><li>In the Netflix series &quot;Black Mirror,&quot; a woman converses with a chatbot version of her late fiancé — and a grieving Canadian man did something similar with his dead girlfriend in real life, the San Fransisco Chronicle <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="reports" data-vars-click-url="https://www.sfchronicle.com/projects/2021/jessica-simulation-artificial-intelligence/" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/projects/2021/jessica-simulation-artificial-intelligence/" target="_blank">reports</a>. </li><li>Other examples: Carrie Fisher being <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="brought back to life" data-vars-click-url="https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/carrie-fisher-oral-history-rise-of-skywalker-star-wars" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/12/carrie-fisher-oral-history-rise-of-skywalker-star-wars" target="_blank">brought back to life</a> as Princess Leia; chef Anthony Bourdain&#x27;s <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="AI voice being used to narrate" data-vars-click-url="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2021/jul/16/anthony-bourdain-documentary-ai-voiceover-roadrunner" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/food/2021/jul/16/anthony-bourdain-documentary-ai-voiceover-roadrunner" target="_blank">AI voice being used to narrate</a> a posthumous documentary about himself.</li></ul><p><strong>What they&#x27;re saying: </strong>&quot;When we learn about some very sophisticated use of AI to copy a real person, such as in the documentary about Anthony Bourdain, we tend to extrapolate from that situation that AI is much better than it really is,&quot; <a class="gtmContentClick" data-vars-link-text="said" data-vars-click-url="https://news.ucr.edu/articles/2021/08/04/artificial-intelligence-bringing-dead-back-life-should-it" data-vars-content-id="16caa38a-8db5-4f02-b330-9e55d48cc770" data-vars-headline="New AI tools let you chat with your dead relatives" data-vars-event-category="story" data-vars-sub-category="story" data-vars-item="in_content_link" href="https://news.ucr.edu/articles/2021/08/04/artificial-intelligence-bringing-dead-back-life-should-it" target="_blank">said</a> Amit Roy-Chowdhury, who chairs the robotics department at the University of California, Riverside. </p><ul><li>&quot;They were only able to do that with Bourdain because there are so many recordings of him in a variety of situations.&quot;</li><li>&quot;In the future, we will probably be able to design AI that responds in a human-like way to new situations, but we don’t know how long this will take.&quot;</li></ul><p><strong>The bottom line: </strong>These kinds of memory-preservation programs &quot;might change the way we collect history,&quot; as Smith put it.</p><ul><li>&quot;We all have amazing stories to tell, and one of the big discoveries I’ve had in founding this company is how few of us truly understand the importance of our own story,&quot; he said. &quot;We’re quite self-deprecating.&quot;</li></ul></div></div><div class="gtmView mt-8 sm:mt-10" data-cy="social-share-bottom" data-vars-category="social_share_bottom"><div class="space-x-4 leading-0"><button aria-label="facebook" class="react-share__ShareButton" style="background-color:transparent;border:none;padding:0;font:inherit;color:inherit;cursor:pointer"><div class="group"><span class="sr-only fixed">Axios on facebook</span><svg class="group-hover:text-white text-soft-black-core" height="32" width="32" viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none"><circle class="stroke-current text-accent-blue-tint" cx="16" cy="16" r="15.5"></circle><circle class="group-hover:fill-soft-black-core" cx="16" cy="16" r="15.5" fill="none"></circle><path fill="currentColor" d="M19 11H17.5C16.837 11 16.2011 11.2634 15.7323 11.7322C15.2634 12.2011 15 12.8369 15 13.5V15H13.5V17H15V21H17V17H18.5L19 15H17V13.5C17 13.3674 17.0527 13.2402 17.1465 13.1464C17.2402 13.0527 17.3674 13 17.5 13H19V11Z"></path></svg></div></button><button aria-label="twitter" class="react-share__ShareButton" style="background-color:transparent;border:none;padding:0;font:inherit;color:inherit;cursor:pointer"><div class="group"><span class="sr-only fixed">Axios on twitter</span><svg class="group-hover:text-white text-soft-black-core" height="32" width="32" viewBox="0 0 32 32" fill="none"><circle class="stroke-current text-accent-blue-tint" cx="16" cy="16" r="15.5"></circle><circle class="group-hover:fill-soft-black-core" cx="16" cy="16" r="15.5" fill="none"></circle><path fill="currentColor" d="M21.5 11.4999C21.0212 11.8376 20.4911 12.0959 19.93 12.2649C19.6289 11.9187 19.2287 11.6732 18.7835 11.5619C18.3384 11.4505 17.8697 11.4785 17.441 11.